chronicles this debate, showing that sex education then, just as in our own era, had as much to do with politics and morals as it did with biology and medicine. Examining how different population groups in the United States were given contrasting types of sex education, Shah demonstrates that such education was used as a tool to reinforce or challenge racial segregation, women's rights, religious diversity, and class identity. Courtney Shah is an instructor of history at Lower Columbia College in Longview, Washington.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRacismxHistoryzUnited States. 0aSex instructionxHistoryzUnited States. 0aSexxHistoryzUnited States. 0aSexually transmitted diseasesxPreventionzUnited States. 4aHistory of Science & Medicine. 4aModern History. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aProgressive Era.  acultural perspectives.  agender roles.  ahistory of sexuality.  amorality and politics.  asex education.  asexual knowledge.  asocial reform.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311143132140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781580468862?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781580468862423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781580468862/original  a978-3-11-143132-1  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles